<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>He told Daily Sun: “On 1 January I was suspicious and visited sangoma Mabhelandile early in the morning. “I found him broke, without a cent, and we had an argument over my money.“I told him one of his trainees, who is related to me, was stealing my money by using her spirit. “Every time she visited my house, my cash would vanish. “So I told him I didn’t want that thwasa in my house.”Mveleli claimed his sangoma then sent another thwasa to steal his money.“He was angry when I left but my sangoma later sent another thwasa to make peace and collect his first trainee’s shoes. “I sat with the second thwasa at the table and she didn’t enter my room. “But as soon as she left my house, my R5 000 was missing. “I rushed to the sangoma’s home and found them drinking booze and braaiing meat. “I confronted him about my missing money. He told me he earns his living by healing, not by stealing.” Sangoma Mabhelandile said: “His clients’ tears create bad luck for him. “He must come clean and bury his poor clients when they die. I have been a sangoma since I was a boy. “I am not a thief. A tokoloshe is stealing his money.”